            <p><name type="place">Washington</name></p>
            <p>May 11, 1896.</p>
            <p>My dear <name type="person">Walsh</name></p>
            <p><name type="person">I</name> am greatly obliged to <name type="person">you</name> for the photograph of <name type="person">Lily</name>. 
                It does not look much like <name type="person">her</name> as <name type="person">I</name> knew
                <name type="person">her</name>, of course, but <name type="person">I</name> am glad to have it. <name type="person">I</name> have written to <name type="person">Mrs. Hirshberg</name>, submitting suggestions
                for beautifying <name type="person">Lily</name>’s grave, and doubtless <name type="person">she</name> will have it looking very pretty by the time that <name type="person">I</name>
                find leisure to write that which will make people go out there to see it.</p>
            <p>Probably <name type="person">I</name> shall be in <name type="place">New York</name> soon, as my work here will be done at the end of the session—
                unless <name type="person">I</name>’m done first. My work has been very hard, and <name type="person">I</name>’m a little broken down.</p>
            <p><name type="person">I</name> hope <name type="person">you</name> sometimes see <name type="person">Leigh</name>. <name type="person">He</name> does not write very often.</p>
            <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
            <p><name type="person">Ambrose Bierce.</name></p>
